where  μ  and  σ2  are  the  mean  and  the  variance  of  the  distribution,  respectively.  While 
CARA  is  a  convenient  assumption,  some  may  ﬁnd  it  more  plausible  that  absolute  risk 
aversion is decreasing with wealth level (DARA), so that richer people take higher risks. 
Indeed,  some may want to normalize the amount of  risk aversion with respect to the 
level  of  wealth.  This  leads  to  the  concept  of  relative  risk  aversion. The  coeﬃcient  of 
relative  risk  aversion  is 

rR (x) = −xu00  (x) /u0 (x) . 
The  constant  relative  risk  aversion  (CRRA)  utility  function  takes  the  form of 

u (x) = −x 1−ρ/ (1 − ρ) , 
where  ρ  is  the  coeﬃcient  of  constant  relative  risk  aversion.  When  ρ  = 1,  it is the  log 
utility  function:  u (x) = log (x). 
